Exp_Guess: I think the study was about how training in any physical activity can improve memory of movement.
Results_Guess: I think the results would show that those with professional training in one or more of these areas have better results with the video than those who are not professionally trained.
Understanding: I think the difficult part was identifying whether or not we were supposed to do the movements during the exercise.
Strategies: I tried to find a pattern with the movements.

Exp_Guess: Ability to recall memory; whether it was strengthened by mirroring the movements. Perhaps this study relates to mirror neurons and their activity.
Results_Guess: That replicating the movements could lead to more accurate memory recall.
Understanding: The expectation to keep our legs and arms moving at a steady pace while we mirrored the actions in the video; should we have been moving while performing the actions or simply during the pauses in between?
Strategies: I tried to use associations of arm and leg movements I'd often seen performed in succession.
Images: These images were a bit confusing on their own but helpful when coupled with explanatory text.

Exp_Guess: How people are able to memorize/recall the order of movements and whether experience (formal training) in a physical activity influences that ability
Results_Guess: I think that people who have experience in sequence/order based physical activity (especially dancers, figure skaters, maybe martial arts) would remember the order of the movements better, and the more experience/time spent doing that sport would also help remembering the order of the movements.
Strategies: I imitated the movements to guess which movement that came next because I did not remember at all.
Images: Yes these images were very helpful. I interpreted the images to say that I should mirror the movements shown.

Understanding: Memorizing the moves in correct order.
Strategies: Went through the sequences in my head
Images: Looked at the stick figures and mimicked the movements

Exp_Guess: How well we can remember movements through memory when acting them out, and this relates to past coordination or training
Results_Guess: Those who have been trained previously in dancing, exercise, etc. would be better at remembering movements through acting them out.
Strategies: Remembering how I moved after each movement

Exp_Guess: Whether you remember the sequences of movement better if you were standing than seated.
Results_Guess: People will remember better when they are standing

Exp_Guess: Difference in learning methods - if being active while being instructed helps people learn activities better or if it distracts them and causes them to forget what they learned while stationary.
Results_Guess: Show that people retained information worse due to the two movement sections than if there was just one sitting section then the questions on sequences. I say this because personally I felt I had a better grasp of the sequence of activities before I had to watch them while walking in place.
Images: They were clear, although the directions were clear enough that the pictures weren't necessary.

Results_Guess: by partaking rather than watching actions you remember them better
Strategies: tried to give moves names to remember them by

Exp_Guess: Whether physical action leads to greater memory
Results_Guess: That physical action does lead to greater memory
Understanding: The shorter videos (11 sec) buffered each time
Strategies: I tried to remember the order by saying it out loud

Exp_Guess: How people understand movement and whether dance or martial arts training has an effect.
Results_Guess: I would've assumed that training in dance or martial arts would help, but I found it very difficult because the movements were being repeated but in isolated videos, I couldn't do it along with the video, and it was stationary.
Understanding: I didn't realize I was looking for smaller patterns within the whole video.
Strategies: I initially tried to remember the pattern, but the video was too long for that. I also tried to visualize myself doing each movement, but moving with the video would've been easier.

Results_Guess: people who do more physical activities have a better chance of remembering the movements
Images: walk in place and move hands as you do so
